\section{Introduction}
% The very first letter is a 2 line initial drop letter followed
% by the rest of the first word in caps.
% 
% form to use if the first word consists of a single letter:
% \IEEEPARstart{A}{demo} file is ....
% 
% form to use if you need the single drop letter followed by
% normal text (unknown if ever used by IEEE):
% \IEEEPARstart{A}{}demo file is ....
% 
% Some journals put the first two words in caps:
% \IEEEPARstart{T}{his demo} file is ....
% 
% Here we have the typical use of a "T" for an initial drop letter
% and "HIS" in caps to complete the first word.
\IEEEPARstart{I}{n} recent years, advances in machine learning
techniques such as Deep Neural Network TODO(chanwcom) 
%cite DNN papers
and enhanced computational power TODO(chanwcom) 
%cite GPU papers
have greatly improved the performance of speech recognition systems
especially in clean environments. Nevertheless, the performance
under noisy environments still needs to be significantly improved
to be useful for far-field speech recognition applications.

Thus far, many researchers have proposed various kinds of algorithms
to address this problem (\emph{e.g.} \cite{P_J_Moreno_ICASSP_1996,
R_M_Stern_ETRW_1997, C_Kim_ASRU_2009_2, C_Kim_ICASSP_2012_1,
C_Kim_ICASSP_2012_2}). To some degrees, these efforts have been
successful for the near-field additive noise, however,
for far-field reverberant speech, the same algorithms usually
haven't shown the same amount of improvement.

Many hearing researchers believe that human perception in 
reverberation is enabled by ``precedence effect", which refers to
an emphasis that appears to be given to the first-arriving
wave-front of a complex signal in sound localization and
possibly speech perception (\emph{e.g.} 
\cite{P_M_Zurek_DirectionalHearing_SpringerVerlag_1987}).
To detect the first wave-front, we can either measure the
envelope of the signal or energy in the frame (\emph{e.g.}
\cite{K_D_Martin_ASPAA_1997, Y_Park_IEICE_ElectronicsExpress_2008})


Motivated by this, in our previous work, we introduced 
an algorithm called Suppression of Slowly varying-components and the Falling
edge of the power envelope (SSF) to enhance speech recognition
accuracy under reverberant environments \cite{C_Kim_INTERSPEECH_2010_2}.
This algorithm has been especially successful for reverberation, but
the processing introduces distortion in the resynthesized speech.
The nonlinear high-pass filtering in \cite{C_Kim_INTERSPEECH_2010_2}
is an effective model to detect the first-arriving wavefront, but
it might not be very close to how actual human beings perceive
sound.

In this paper, we introduce a new algorithm named Temporal
Masking and Thresholding (TMT). In this algorithm,
temporal masks are constructed to suppress reflected wave files
under reverberant environments. We estimate the perceived 
peak sound level after applying the power-law nonlinearity,
and apply a temporal masking based on this. We also apply 
thresholding based on the peak power.

%\begin{figure}
%    \begin{center}
%    \resizebox{60mm}{!}{\input{../figures/TMT_block_diagram.tex}}
%    \caption {
%    		The structure of the TMT algorithm to obtain the normalized 
%    		speech from the original input speech.
%    	}
%    	\label{fig:TMT_block_diagram}
%    \end{center} \vspace{-5mm}
%\end{figure}
%
%
%

However, in the real situations, even if the target is located along
the perpendicular bisector of the line connecting two microphones,
the phase difference would not be zero. 
Even if two microphones are of the same model, these real two microphones
are not exactly identical in physical characteristics, and
the recording circuity may also add some non-uniform delay.

