\subsection{Review on finding the from the phase difference}
\label{sec:review_}

In this section, we review the procedure TODO(chanwcom) citing references.
TODO(chanwcom) Also look at some of my previous papers.
%
Let $x_0[n]$ and $x_1[n]$ represent signals from the left and right
microphones, respectively. To represent the narrowband short-time signals,
we use the symbols $x_0[n; m, \omega_k]$ and 
$x_1[n; m, \omega_k]$, respectively, where $m$ is the frame index,
and $\omega_k$ is the discrete-time frequency defined by 
$\omega_k = \frac{2 \pi k}{N}, 0 \le k \le N - 1$. These signals are
narrowband signals centered at frequency $\omega_k$.



Suppose that we have signals from a pair of microphones represented by
$X_0[m, e^{j \omega_k})$ and $X_1[m, e^{j \omega_k})$.
Suppose that we have signals the two microphones represented by
$x_0[n]$ and $x_1[n]$. By applying successive Hamming windows to the
speech signals, we obtain the Short-Time Fouer
TODO(chanwcom) citing the SMAD paper, and also all of my previous papers
Suppose that $X_0[m, e^{j \omega_k})$ and $X_1[m, e^{j \omega_k})$.
We refer to $\tau[m, e^{j \omega_k})$ as the ITD at frame index at $m$
and frequency $\omega_k$. Then
Suppose that 


As the simplest case, suppose that we have two signals 
$x_0[n; m, \omega_k)$ and
$x_1[n; m, \omega_k)$. 
\begin{eqnarray}
  x_0[n; m, \omega_k] = x_1[n - \tau[m, \omega_k); m, \omega_k]
    \label{eq:two_mic_signals_time_domain}
\end{eqnarray}
Performing the Fourier transform of \eqref{eq:two_mic_signals_time_domain},
 we obtain the following relation:
\begin{eqnarray}
  X_0[m, e^{j \omega_k})
      = e^{-j \omega_k \tau[m, \omega_k)} X_1[m; e^{j \omega_k})
    \label{eq:two_mic_signals_freq_domain}
\end{eqnarray}
%
From \eqref{eq:two_mic_signals_freq_domain}, we find that the phase
difference between two spectra is given by the following equation:
\begin{eqnarray}
  \Delta \phi[m, e^{j \omega_k}) & = & \angle{X_L[m, e^{j \omega_k})}
      - \angle{X_R[m, e^{j \omega_k})} \nonumber \\
               & = & \omega_k \tau[m, e^{j \omega_k})  + 2 \pi l
\end{eqnarray}
where $l$ is an integer.

We define $\phi_{\tau}[m, e^{j \omega_k})$ as follows \cite{C_Kim_ICASSP_2012_2}:
\begin{eqnarray}
  \phi_{\tau}[m, e^{j \omega_k}) = 
    \begin{cases}
        \Delta \phi[m, e^{j \omega_k}),   \\
            \qquad \text{if } \big| \Delta \phi[m, e^{j \omega_k}) \big|
                \le \pi  \\
        \Delta \phi[m, e^{j \omega_k}) - 2 \pi,    \\
            \qquad \text{if } \Delta \phi[m, e^{j \omega_k}) 
                \ge \pi  \\
        \Delta \phi[m, e^{j \omega_k}) + 2 \pi,    \\
              \qquad \text{if } \Delta \phi[m, e^{j \omega_k})  \le -\pi 
    \end{cases}  
\end{eqnarray}

As shown in Fig. \ref{fig:two_mics_block_diagram},
if the sound source is located along a line of angle 
$\theta[m, \omega_k)$, with respect to the perpendicular 
bisector to the line between two
 microphones, geometric consideration determine the ITD in the
discrete-time domain $\tau[m, \omega_k)$ to be 
\begin{eqnarray}
  \tau[m, \omega_k) 
      = \frac{d \sin \left( \theta[m, \omega_k )  \right) f_s}
          {c_{air}}
\end{eqnarray}


The above relation may be simplified using the modular operation:
\begin{eqnarray}
  \phi_{\tau}[m, \omega_k) 
      = \left[\left(
          \Delta \phi[m, e^{j \omega_k}) + \pi\right) \mod 2 \pi \right]
              - \pi
\end{eqnarray}
where $\mod$ is a modulo operation.

The relationship between $\theta$ and $\phi$ is given as 
follows \cite{C_Kim_ICASSP_2012_2}:
\begin{eqnarray}
  \theta[m, e^{j \omega_k}) = \sin^{(-1)} 
      \left(  
          \frac{c_{air} \phi_{\tau}[m, e^{j \omega_k})}{\omega_k f_s d} 
              \right)
\end{eqnarray}
where $c_{air}$ is the speed of the sound air (assumed to be 343.0 $m/s$ 
in our work) and $f_s$ is the sampling rate, and $d$ is the distance 
between two microphones. In our work, we used the distance of 
$d = 0.02 \, m$.


