In this section, we describe how to estimate the phase offset 
$\theta_o(\omega_k)$ at the frequency $\omega_k$.
For each channel $l$, we collect the following data:
$\phi[m, e^{j \omega_k}), $.
For each frequency component we apply weighted averaging.

\begin{figure}
    \begin{center}
    \resizebox{35mm}{!}{\input{../figures/two_mics.tex}}
    \caption {
        Two microphones and a sound source
    	}
    	\label{fig:two_mics_block_diagram}
    \end{center} \vspace{-5mm}
\end{figure}

Many researchers have tried to describe how the physical 
frequency of an incoming signal is related to the representation 
of that frequency by the human auditory system.  
As one of such works, Moore and Glasberg \cite{B_C_J_Moore_ActaAcustica_1996}, 
proposed the Equivalent Rectangular Bandwidth (ERB) scale modifying Zwickerâ€™s loudness model. 
The ERB scale is a measure that gives
an approximation to the bandwidth of filters in human hearing using 
rectangular bandpass filters; several different approximations of 
the ERB scale exist. The following relation is used in our work
to relate the frequency $f$ in $Hz$ with the ERB rate scale $r$
 \cite{M_Brookes_VoiceBox}:
\begin{eqnarray}
  r & = & \text{ERBS}(f) \nonumber  \\
    & = & 11.17268 \ln\left(1 + \frac{46.06538 f}{f + 14678.49} \right) \\
  f & = & \text{ERBS}^{-1}(r) \nonumber \\
    & = & \frac{676170.4}{47.06538-\exp\left(0.08950404 - r \right)} \nonumber \\ 
    &   &   - 14678.49 
\end{eqnarray}
where $f$ is the frequency in $kHz$. Fig. \ref{fig:plot_freq_vs_erb} shows the relation
between the frequency and the ERB scale.
%
%
%
\begin{figure}
    \begin{center}
    {\includegraphics[width=65mm]{../figures/plot_freq_vs_erb.eps}}  \\
    \caption {
        The relationship between the frequency ({\it Hz }) and 
        the ERB scale.
    	}
    	\label{fig:plot_freq_vs_erb}
    \end{center} 
\end{figure}
%
%
%
\begin{eqnarray}
  \Phi = \left\{ \phi \Big| \phi_t - \frac{\phi_w}{2}  \le \phi \le \phi_t + \frac{\phi_w}{2} \right\}
\end{eqnarray}
We convert the linear frequency into the Equivalent Rectangular Bandwidth
(ERB) scale, 


We define the following terms:
\begin{eqnarray}
  \psi[m, e^{j\omega_k}) & = &
        \mathds{1}_{\Phi} 
        (\phi[m, e^{j\omega_k'}]) \big|X_A[m,  e^{j\omega_k'})\big|^ 2 \nonumber \\
                         & &   \times  \phi[m, e^{j\omega_k'}] \\
  \xi[m, e^{j\omega_k}) & = &
        \mathds{1}_{\Phi}(\phi[m, e^{j\omega_k'}])
            \big|X_A[m,  e^{j\omega_k'})\big|^2
\end{eqnarray}
where $\mathds{1}()$ is the indicator function.

\begin{eqnarray}
  \phi_o(\omega_k) = 
      \frac{
          \sum_{m = 0} ^ {M - 1} 
              \sum_{k' = g\left(l\left(\omega_k\right)\right)}
                  ^{g\left(u(\omega_k)\right)} 
                      \psi[m, e^{j\omega_k})
            }
            {
              \sum_{m = 0} ^ {M - 1} 
                  \sum_{k' = g\left(l\left(\omega_k\right)\right)}
                      ^{g\left(u(\omega_k)\right)} 
                          \xi[m, e^{j\omega_k})
            }
\end{eqnarray}
where $l(\omega_k)$ is defined as follows: 
\begin{eqnarray}
  l(\omega_k) = \frac{2 \pi}{f_s} \text{ERBS}^{-1}
      \left(\max\left\{r(\omega_k) - \frac{b}{2}, 0 \right\}\right)
\end{eqnarray}
where $r$ is defined by:
\begin{eqnarray}
  r(\omega_k) = \text{ERBS} \left(\frac{\omega_k}{2 \pi} f_s\right) 
\end{eqnarray}
Similarly, $u(\omega_k)$ are defined as follows: 
\begin{eqnarray}
  u(\omega_k) = \frac{2 \pi}{f_s} \text{ERBS}^{-1}
      \left(r(\omega_k) + b \right)
\end{eqnarray}
$g(\omega)$ is a function to obtain the discrete frequency index $k$
from the discrete-time frequency $\omega$. Since the relation is given by
$\omega = \frac{2 \pi k}{N}$, $g(\omega)$ is defined as follows:
\begin{eqnarray}
  k = g(\omega) = \left\lceil\frac{\omega N}{2 \pi} + 0.5\right\rceil
\end{eqnarray}
where $N$ is the FFT size.
Usually, the phase offset is a function of the frequency $\omega_k$,
thus we represent it by $\theta_o(l)$. 

