\subsection{Gammatone frequency integration and auditory nonlinearity}
%
As shown in Fig. \ref{fig:TMT_block_diagram}, the first step
of TMT processing is performing Short-Time Fourier Transform (STFT) using
Hamming windows of duration 100 ms. We use this medium-duration window 
which is longer than those used in ordinary speech processing, since 
it has been frequently observed that medium-duration windows are better
suited for noise suppression \cite{C_Kim_INTERSPEECH_2009_1, 
C_Kim_ASRU_2009_1}.
%
%
TODO(chanwcom) % Check what would be a good window length.
 As in \cite{C_Kim_IEEETran_2014_1}, the gammatone spectral integration
is done by the following equation:
%
\begin{eqnarray}
  P[m, l] = \sum_{k = 0}^{K / 2}
      \Big| X[m, e^{j \omega_k}] H_l(e^{j \omega_k}) \Big|^2  
          \label{eq:spectral_integration}
\end{eqnarray}
%
where $K$ is the DFT size, $m$ and $l$ represent the frame and
channel indices respectively. $\omega_k$ is a discrete-frequency
defined by $\omega_k = \frac{2 \pi k}{K}$, and $H_l(e^{j \omega_k})$
is the gammatone response for the $l$-th channel. $P[m, l]$ is the
power obtained for the time-frequency bin $[m, l]$.

The gammatone responses $H_l(e^{j \omega_k})$ are slightly different
from those used in our previous research in \cite{C_Kim_IEEETran_2014_1,
C_Kim_ASRU_2009_2}. The frequency responses are modified to satisfy
the following constraint:
%
\begin{eqnarray}
  \sum_{l = 0}^{L - 1} H(e^{j \omega_k}) = 1.  \label{eq:unity_constraint}
\end{eqnarray}
%
where $L$ is the number of the gammatone channels. The reason for this
constraint will be explained in Sec. \ref{sec:spectral_reshaping}.
Even though frequency responses $Q_l(e^{j \omega_k})$ of an ordinary 
filter bank usually do not satisfy \eqref{eq:unity_constraint}, we may 
normalize the filter response to make them satisfy 
\eqref{eq:unity_constraint} by normalizing them as follows:
%
\begin{eqnarray} 
    H_l(e^{j\omega_k}) = \frac{\big|Q_l(e^{j\omega_k}) \big|}
        {\sum_{l = 0}^{L - 1} \big| Q_l(e^{j\omega_k}) \big|}.
\end{eqnarray}
%
Since the power $P[m, l]$ in \eqref{eq:spectral_integration} is not
directly related to how human beings perceive the sound level, we
apply the power function based nonlinearity \cite{C_Kim_PhDThesis,
C_Kim_IEEETran_2014_1}.
\begin{eqnarray}
  S[m, l] = P[m, l]^{a_0}     \label{eq:compressive_nonlinearity}  
\end{eqnarray}
As in \cite{C_Kim_IEEETran_2014_1, C_Kim_INTERSPEECH_2010_1, 
C_Kim_ICASSP_2010_1}, 
we use the power coefficient of $a_0 = \frac{1}{15}$.

\subsection{Peak sound level estimation and binary mask generation}
\label{sec:peak_sound_level_estimation}

From $S[m, l]$, we obtain the peak sound level for each channel
$l$. The peak sound level is the upper envelope of the $S[m, l]$
as shown in Fig. TODO(chanwcom) XXX. We use the following simple
mathematical model.
\begin{eqnarray}
  T[m, l] = \max(\lambda T[m - 1, l], S[m, l]) 
\end{eqnarray}
Using the peak sound level $T[m, l]$, the binary mask $\mu[m, l]$ 
is constructed using the following criterion:
\begin{eqnarray}
  \mu[m, l] = 
  \begin{cases}
      1, \qquad \text{if } S[m, l] \ge T[m, l]  \\
      0, \qquad \text{if } S[m, l] < T[m, l].
        \label{eq:binary_masking_coeff}
  \end{cases} 
\end{eqnarray}
In our previous SSF algorithm \cite{C_Kim_INTERSPEECH_2010_2}, we
used the 1st-order IIR lowpass filter output for a similar purpose,
but in this work, we use a model more closely related to human 
perception.
In binary masking, it has been frequently observed that 
a suitable flooring is necessary (\emph{e.g.}\cite{C_Kim_INTERSPEECH_2009_1, 
C_Kim_ICASSP_2012_2}). In many previous approaches, usually
fixed multiplier values like 0.01, or 0.001 were used for masked
time-frequency bins to prevent them from having zero power 
(\emph{e.g.} \cite{C_Kim_INTERSPEECH_2009_1}). 
In TMT algorithm, instead of using such scaling constants, we use a 
a threshold power level $\rho[m, l]$, which depends on the peak sound
level $T[m, l]$ for each time-frequency bin:
\begin{eqnarray}
  \rho[m, l] = \rho_0 {T[m, l]}^{\frac{1}{a_0}}
            \label{eq:flooring_level}
\end{eqnarray}
where $a_0$ is the power coefficient for the compressive nonlinearty 
in \eqref{eq:compressive_nonlinearity}. Since the compressive nonlineary
is expanded in \eqref{eq:flooring_level}, it is evident that the 
threshold power level $\rho[m, l]$ is 30 dB below the time-varying 
peak power. 
This thresholding scheme is also motivated by human auditory masking
effect.
We believe this thresholding approach is closer to the actual human
perception rather than just using some fixed constants like 0.01. 

The final masking coefficients $\mu_f[m, l]$ are obtained using
the threshold level $\rho[m, l]$ as follows:
\begin{eqnarray}
    \mu_f[m, l] = \max \left(\mu[m, l], \frac{\rho[m, l]}{P[m, l]}  \right).
\end{eqnarray}
where $P[m, l]$ is the power in the time-frequency bin $[m, l]$ in 
\eqref{eq:spectral_integration}.

%
%
%
\subsection{Spectral reshaping}
  \label{sec:spectral_reshaping}
%
Using the $\mu[m, l]$ masking coefficients obtained in 
\eqref{eq:binary_masking_coeff}, we obtain the enhanced spectrum 
$Y[m, l]$ using the spectral reshaping technique 
\cite{C_Kim_ASRU_2009_2, C_Kim_INTERSPEECH_2010_2}. 
\begin{eqnarray}
  Y[m, e^{j \omega_k}) = \sum_{l = 0}^{L - 1} 
      \left( \sqrt{\mu_f[m, l]} X[m, e^{j \omega_k})
           H_l(e^{j \omega_k}) \right)  
              \label{eq:spectral_reshaping}
\end{eqnarray}
We square rooted the floored masking coefficient $\mu_f[m, l]$ in
the above equation, because, the masking coefficients in Sec.
\ref{sec:peak_sound_level_estimation} is defined for power.
Now, it is time to discuss why the unity constraint in 
\eqref{eq:unity_constraint} needs to hold for the frequency 
responses.
In \eqref{eq:spectral_reshaping}, if $\mu_f[m, l] = 1$ for 
all $0 \le l \le L - 1$ at a certain frame $m$, then we expect
the output $Y[m, e^{j \omega_k})$ to be the same as the input
$X[m, e^{j \omega_k})$. From this, it is obvious that the 
filter bank needs to satisfy \eqref{eq:unity_constraint}. 
As before, $m$ and $l$ are the frame and channel indices, and $L$ is the
number of channels.  After obtaining the enhanced spectrum $Y[m, l]$, 
the output speech is resynthesized using the IFFT and the OverLap 
Addition (OLA).

In Fig. \label{fig:comparisons_of_spectrograms}, we compare the
spectrograms obtained from the original clean speech 
(Fig. \ref{fig:clean_speech_spectrogram}),
from the reverberant speech
(Fig. \ref{fig:reverb_speech_spectrogram}), and
the same reverberant speech when processed with this TMT processing
(Fig. \ref{fig:tmt_reverb_speech_spectrogram}). The reverberation
time ($T_{60}$) is 500 {\it ms}. As can clearly seen in these figures,
TMT processing has the effect of keeping the first arriving wavefront
and suppressing the following reflected waves.

